idea:
In Week 1 you hardcoded everything — 'standard_user', 'secret_sauce', typed directly into your test. That works once. It breaks the moment you need the same value in five places and have to change all five by hand.

A variable is just a labelled box that holds a value. Instead of writing 'standard_user' six times, you write it once, put it in a box called username, and use the box everywhere.

const username = 'standard_user';
const password = 'secret_sauce';

const means "this box's contents won't change during this test." That's the only keyword you need this week — let means "this box's contents might change," and you'll meet it on Day 10 when you actually need that flexibility. Until then, default to const. I tell every mentee: const until you have a reason not to.

codeRaw:
const { test, expect } = require('@playwright/test');

test('user can log in to Sauce Demo', async ({ page }) => {
  const username = 'standard_user';
  const password = 'secret_sauce';
  const baseUrl = 'https://www.saucedemo.com';

  await page.goto(baseUrl);
  await page.fill('#user-name', username);
  await page.fill('#password', password);
  await page.click('#login-button');

  await expect(page).toHaveURL(baseUrl + '/inventory.html');
});

idea:
You now have two test files that both start with the same three lines: navigate, fill username, fill password, click login. That's not a coincidence — almost every test you'll ever write against Sauce Demo starts with logging in.

A function is a named, reusable block of code. Instead of retyping the login steps every time, you wrap them once in async function login(page, username, password) { ... }. Then anywhere you need to log in, you just call: await login(page, 'standard_user', 'secret_sauce');

One line instead of four. The function is the box; username and password are the inputs you hand it — these are called parameters.

codeRaw:
const { test, expect } = require('@playwright/test');

async function login(page, username, password) {
  await page.goto('https://www.saucedemo.com');
  await page.fill('#user-name', username);
  await page.fill('#password', password);
  await page.click('#login-button');
}

test('standard user logs in successfully', async ({ page }) => {
  await login(page, 'standard_user', 'secret_sauce');
  await expect(page).toHaveURL(
    'https://www.saucedemo.com/inventory.html'
  );
});

test('locked out user sees error', async ({ page }) => {
  await login(page, 'locked_out_user', 'secret_sauce');
  await expect(page.locator('[data-test="error"]'))
    .toContainText('locked out');
});

async function loginAndCheck(page, username) {
  await page.goto('https://www.saucedemo.com');
  await page.fill('#user-name', username);
  await page.fill('#password', 'secret_sauce');
  await page.click('#login-button');

  if (username === 'locked_out_user') {
    await expect(page.locator('[data-test="error"]')).toBeVisible();
  } else {
    await expect(page).toHaveURL('https://www.saucedemo.com/inventory.html');
  }
}

idea:
Imagine testing that all six products on the Sauce Demo inventory page have a visible "Add to cart" button. You could write six nearly-identical assertions. Or you could put your six product names in a list — an array — and loop over it.

for (const product of products) { console.log(product); }

Read it as: "for each product in this list of products, do the thing inside the curly braces." The loop runs once per item, automatically. Three products, three lines saved you from writing three nearly-identical blocks of code.

codeRaw:
const { test, expect } = require('@playwright/test');

test('all products show an add to cart button', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://www.saucedemo.com');
  await page.fill('#user-name', 'standard_user');
  await page.fill('#password', 'secret_sauce');
  await page.click('#login-button');

  const productNames = await page
    .locator('.inventory_item_name')
    .allTextContents();

  for (const name of productNames) {
    console.log('Checking product:', name);
  }

  expect(productNames.length).toBeGreaterThan(0);
});

idea:
Yesterday you tested four postal code values. If you wrote four separate test() blocks with the logic copy-pasted each time, you repeated yourself — the exact problem functions solved for you back on Day 9.

The fix: keep your test data in an array, and loop the same test logic over every value.

const postalCodes = [
  { value: '', label: 'empty' },
  { value: '1', label: 'single character' },
  { value: '6'.repeat(50), label: 'fifty characters' },
  { value: '600001', label: 'normal value' }
];

for (const code of postalCodes) {
  test the postal code using code.value and code.label
}

Same idea as Day 11's loop, applied to test generation itself instead of just assertions inside one test.

