idea:
Not all assertions are equally useful. Consider these two:

await expect(page.locator('.error')).toBeVisible();
await expect(page.locator('.error')).toContainText('Username is required');

The first only checks that SOME error showed up. The second checks that the RIGHT error showed up. I've seen tests pass the first version while displaying the completely wrong error message — a real bug the test was structurally incapable of catching, because it never looked closely enough.

I call this a weak assertion: technically true, practically useless. A strong assertion checks the specific, meaningful detail that would actually indicate something is wrong.

A Page Object is a class that represents one page of your app — its selectors live inside the class, as properties, and its actions live inside the class, as methods. Your tests stop knowing what a selector even is. They just call methods.

class LoginPage {
  constructor(page) {
    this.page = page;
    this.usernameInput = page.locator('#user-name');
    this.passwordInput = page.locator('#password');
    this.loginButton = page.locator('#login-button');
  }

  async login(username, password) {
    await this.page.goto('https://www.saucedemo.com');
    await this.usernameInput.fill(username);
    await this.passwordInput.fill(password);
    await this.loginButton.click();
  }
}

Notice: this is your Day 9 login() function, reshaped into a class. You already understood the core idea — this just gives it a home where selectors live exactly once.

